1290,IssuesEvent,2017-07-17 17:16:36+00:00,15367540,jruizgit/rules,12946220,macroach,,,closed,Is priority (salience) working properly?,[],[],4,"Hi @jruizgit, I've been playing with rule priority levels, and in the following example is not behaving the way I would expect. The conditions for both `rule1` and `rule2` are met after the initial fact is asserted, and so I would expect the one with the lower priority value (`rule2`) to fire, but `rule1` is triggered instead. Assuming this isn't a bug, would you mind explaining what is happening so that I can better understand the logic around rule priority/execution?

```
from durable.lang import *

with ruleset('ex3'):

    @when_all(
        pri(2),
        c.fact1 << m.toggle == True,
        none(+m.cancel)
    )
    def rule1(c):
        c.assert_fact({""cancel"":True})
        print(""rule1 fired"")

    @when_all(
        pri(1),
        none(+m.cancel)
    )
    def rule2(c):
        c.assert_fact({""cancel"":True})
        print(""rule2 fired"")


    @when_start
    def start(host):
        x = host.assert_fact(""ex3"",{""toggle"":True})

run_all()
```
Output:
```
 * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/ (Press CTRL+C to quit)
rule1 fired
```

Many thanks,
Mac",{},{}
1310,IssuesEvent,2015-04-27 16:45:36+00:00,8323977,metachris/RPIO,12139975,clrdls,,,opened,P5 pins no longer work as interrupts,[],[],0,"In March I did an apt-get update, apt-get upgrade, and apt-get dist-upgrade prior to installing database software.  I had GPIO 28 on the P5 header programmed as a interrupt callback using RPIO and it stopped working.  I noticed one message that said interrupt 50 was disabled in the kernel.  I moved the wire to GPIO 11 on the P1 header, edited the program and it worked as before.  I checked GPIO 29 on the P5 header and it did not work as an interrupt either. I don't know if the P5 pins work as standard IO points. I assume that the upgrades caused the problem,  I2C was also disabled but I was able to turn it back on using raspi-config.  Any ideas on how to make the P5 pins usable again?
Thanks",{},{}
