2323,IssuesEvent,2016-08-14 22:30:10+00:00,41179827,Rapptz/discord.py,1695103,Rapptz,,,opened,Snowflake IDs should not be strings,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Rapptz/discord.py/labels/breaking%20change', 'name': 'breaking change', 'color': 'e99695'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Rapptz/discord.py/labels/RFC', 'name': 'RFC', 'color': 'fbca04'}]",[],0,"Currently IDs are implemented as `str` because that is what the API returns it as. This can lead to some confusion or storage woes depending.

In reality, IDs are snowflakes which are 64-bit unsigned integers. So they should ideally be at least `int`. This comes with certain benefits:

- Faster hashing (O(1) vs O(n))
- Faster comparisons (O(1) vs O(n))
- Less memory consumption (28 bytes vs 49 + 16-19 bytes)

The standard `json` module allows for 64-bit integers as values, but the `json` module does not allow `int` keys since the JSON spec only allows string keys. Due to this, there may be some woes from the user end if they're using JSON storage using IDs as keys. Said users should cast it to `str` instead.

A proposed question must be taken into consideration before going through with this change in the future:

- Should the ID type be `int` or a subclass of `int` (i.e. `Snowflake`) with certain member functions?

The memory consumption of an ID if the type was `int` would be 28 bytes but it would increase to 52 bytes if it was a subclass. Otherwise the subclass would behave the same as the `int`.",{},{}
