2844,IssuesEvent,2015-09-11 20:13:06+00:00,5598737,BurntSushi/nflgame,2996205,ochawkeye,,,opened,nflgame-update-players BeautifulSoup warning,[],[],0,">     Explicit is better than implicit.

Running nflgame-update-players warns about no parser being explicitly specified.  This could (though not likely in this use case) lead to unexpected behavior.

Regardless, not explicitly specifying a parser is leading to an ""ugly"" BeautifulSoup warning which depends on which parsers are
```
D:\Python27\lib\site-packages\bs4\__init__.py:166: UserWarning: No parser was explicitly specified, so I'm using the bes
t available HTML parser for this system (""html.parser""). This usually isn't a problem, but if you run this code on anoth
er system, or in a different virtual environment, it may use a different parser and behave differently.

To get rid of this warning, change this:

 BeautifulSoup([your markup])

to this:

 BeautifulSoup([your markup], ""html.parser"")

  markup_type=markup_type))
```

or
```
/home/dan/.local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/bs4/__init__.py:166: UserWarning: No parser was explicitly specified, so I'm using the best available HTML parser for this system (""lxml""). This usually isn't a problem, but if you run this code on another system, or in a different virtual environment, it may use a different parser and behave differently.

To get rid of this warning, change this:

 BeautifulSoup([your markup])

to this:

 BeautifulSoup([your markup], ""lxml"")

  markup_type=markup_type))
```

I have not noticed any downside to using `html.parser`, though if `lxml` is desired it should probably be made a dependency.

I believe only lines affected are in update_players.py: [line 123](https://github.com/BurntSushi/nflgame/blob/df86c03855583695c4e7f2226464bf349ece7bfc/nflgame/update_players.py#L123) and [line 193](https://github.com/BurntSushi/nflgame/blob/df86c03855583695c4e7f2226464bf349ece7bfc/nflgame/update_players.py#L193)",{},{}
2860,IssuesEvent,2017-02-24 15:33:02+00:00,1938370,Mottie/tablesorter,6368249,MitoG,,,opened,Filter not working when multiple filters have the same values,[],[],0,"Hello,

while working with the tablesorter.widget.filter.js I came accross a situation where the table would not be filtered when the filter was changed.

### Example:
Type | Priority
------------ | -------------
Foo | Low
Bar | Medium
FooBar | High

In this example each row is assigned a value `0 | 1 | 2` so `Foo` and `Low` would both be assigned the value `0`

Type | Priority | Value (for both columns)
------------ | ------------- | -------------
Foo | Low | 0
Bar | Medium | 1
FooBar | High | 2

Now if you were to set the `Type` filter to `Foo` intern the variable `combinedFilters` would contain the value `0` since it's a joined array of all filter values.
This happens twice actually:
[widget-filter.js Line: 886](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L886): `combinedFilters = ( filters || [] ).join( '' );`
[widget-filter.js Line: 1314](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L1314): `combinedFilters = ( filters || [] ).join( '' );`

After filtering, the value of `combinedFilters` will be written into `c.lastCombinedFilter`
[widget-filter.js Line: 1502](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L1502): `c.lastCombinedFilter = combinedFilters;`

If the next filter you set would also be of the value `0` the code would check if the values of the newly written `combinedFilters` would equal the value of `c.lastCombinedFilter`

[widget-filter.js Line: 910-912](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L910-L912):
```javascript
if ( c.lastCombinedFilter === combinedFilters && filter !== false ) 
{
    return;
}
```
Now both variables would be `0` so the code returns without filtering the table by the new filter.


### Solution:

In my project I changed the line [886](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L886): and [1314](https://github.com/Mottie/tablesorter/blob/master/js/widgets/widget-filter.js#L1314): to 
`combinedFilters = ( filters || [] ).join( ',' );`

As I don't know if there is a better way to solve this I have not submitted a pull-request, I'll leave this to the people who know javascript.",{},{}
