3142,IssuesEvent,2016-05-27 17:47:35+00:00,20571759,rosenbrockc/fortpy,7817795,rosenbrockc,,,closed,`Too many open files` Error,[],[],1,"When executing the unit tests in the new multi-processing mode, `fortpy` was crashing with the `Too many open files` OS error. I updated all the `Popen` calls to include the `close_fds` directive. I also explicitly closed the `PIPE` redirects from those processes. That helped, but we still couldn't get through all the unit tests on a big library (with some `10,000`s of test cases) without the error happening (on 4 cores).

I concluded that I just needed to up the limit for my user account. I increased it with `ulimit -n 1024` and that worked. Analysis with `lsof` shows that all the python instances (when running in parallel) were using about `100` per core used in the unit tests. This will obviously vary with the library being tested and the structure of the executables etc. (how many files `fortran` is keeping open during execution) as well as how many cores are running.",{},{}
