3437,IssuesEvent,2017-05-11 18:29:20+00:00,41542522,cztomczak/cefpython,1187415,cztomczak,,,closed,Drag & drop in OSR mode (Kivy). Merge patch into upstream.,"[{'id': 473567830, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cztomczak/cefpython/labels/next%20release', 'name': 'next release', 'color': 'bfe5bf', 'default': False}, {'id': 502569374, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cztomczak/cefpython/labels/off-screen%20rendering', 'name': 'off-screen rendering', 'color': 'dddddd', 'default': False}, {'id': 502495732, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/cztomczak/cefpython/labels/patch%20upstream', 'name': 'patch upstream', 'color': 'c7def8', 'default': False}]",[],10,"Drag & drop doesn't work in upstream cefclient on Linux, two related topics on the CEF Forum:
- https://magpcss.org/ceforum/viewtopic.php?f=6&t=14393&p=31801#p31801
- https://magpcss.org/ceforum/viewtopic.php?f=6&t=14464

Two commits in upstream that added d&d support in OSR mode on Windows and Mac:
- In branch 1916: [1] https://bitbucket.org/chromiumembedded/cef/commits/998fa796ca69210baf0072e1141f9fc2c6e0d413?at=1916
- In master: [2] https://bitbucket.org/chromiumembedded/cef/commits/dea4daffd71be5262cf42fa8f3ba6a93d0465c9f?at=master

On Mac drag-image representation is not implemented (upstream [Issue #1715](https://bitbucket.org/chromiumembedded/cef/issues/1715)). On Windows looks like there is drag-image representation (I haven't tested), but from looking at the code it is implemented using Windows API specific functions (probably IE html parser that might not be reliable that much), and such functions are not available on Linux / Mac (d&d OS APIs). 

On Linux there is an issue with d&d in Chrome/cefclient in windowed-mode in the html5demos drag example - the drag-image representation is missing. Looks like this is some issue with that example.

I am testing d&d with these two examples:
- https://mdn.github.io/drag-and-drop/copy-move-DataTransfer.html
- http://html5demos.com/drag

Drag & drop in OSR Kivy was implemented in CEF Python in these commits:
- 7b2b8f5a205440a6d8eec2a7d1ba5307a22b14f8
- 8bd800f2d6f3a73255c5d06925704ac3465276c7
- 21549c7adc36035717e4c71799ccabcc95092d4b

There is still missing the drag-image representation. Currently a custom drag-drop icon is displayed during drag.

In cefclient to implement d&d in OSR on Linux it would be required to use OS d&d functions to register the window as draggable, similarly was done for Win/Mac (links [1], [2] posted at the beginning of the post). Below is a bunch of links on how to do that:
- Drag & drop tutorial from a book: http://www.compsci.hunter.cuny.edu/~sweiss/course_materials/csci493.70/lecture_notes/GTK_dragndrop.pdf
- GTK 2 manual links:
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gtk2/stable/
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gtk2/stable/gtk2-Drag-and-Drop.html
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gtk2/stable/gtk2-Selections.html
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gtk2/stable/gtk2-Signals.html
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gdk2/stable/
  - https://developer.gnome.org/gdk2/stable/gdk2-Drag-and-Drop.html
- Useful sources implementing GTK d&d:
  - https://github.com/LuaDist/wxwidgets/blob/master/src/gtk/dnd.cpp
  - http://www.scintilla.org/ScintillaGTK.cxx
",{},{}
3444,IssuesEvent,2016-12-30 18:28:39+00:00,59388509,dgilland/sqlservice,701548,DanCardin,,,closed,How to create model instances which are many-to-many,[],[],4,"In the docs it says `model.update` works for 1:1 and 1:m, but is there a nice way to ensure the mapping table rows are inserted in a m:m relation?

Right now, I just created an association model and set up the relation so it points to the mapping table. Something along the lines of 
```python
class Parent(models.Model):
    __tablename__ = 'parent'

    id = Column(types.Integer(), primary_key=True, autoincrement=True)

    children = orm.relation('Association')


class Association(models.Model):
    __tablename__ = 'association'
    parent_id = Column(types.Integer(), ForeignKey('parent.id'), primary_key=True)
    child_id = Column(types.Integer(), ForeignKey('child.id'), primary_key=True)

    children = orm.relation('Child')
```
and
```python
parent = models.Parent(dict(
    children=[{'child_id': _id} for _id in ids],
))
```

but it would be nice to be able to ignore the existence (for the most part) of the mapping table like normal.",{},{}
