3655,IssuesEvent,2016-06-15 18:13:14+00:00,16967699,prjemian/spec2nexus,2279984,prjemian,,,closed,Should undefined key cause failure?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/prjemian/spec2nexus/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],2,"I have now had to work with reading files for two different beamlines, both using some non-standard keys in the spec file.  When the current implementation encountered the SpecDataFile object fails on UnknownSpecFilePart exception and it looks like file parsing stops at this point.  This ultimately occurs at Line 353 of spec.py.  With the number of beamline defined keys out there I wonder if failing is always the best option.  For many programs it may be better to skip the line an report the undefined part.  I know writing a plugin is the solution for this but wonder if it should always be necessary.  Could there, be a user defined handler for these lines so that the program goes on.  The default handler could fail as it does now and perhaps one could be provided to report the line and then continue.",{},{}
3658,IssuesEvent,2017-09-07 12:49:47+00:00,65724446,psycofdj/coverxygen,1496191,psycofdj,,,reopened,Integration with codecov.io,[],[],1,"See codecov/support#364, in short coverxygen can be used to get doxygen coverage numbers on codecov.io by simply adding something like:
```
make doxygen
python -m coverxygen --xml-dir xml/ --src-dir . --output doxygen.coverage.info
bash <(curl -s https://codecov.io/bash) -R . -F doxygen -X gcov -f doxygen.coverage.info
```

",{},{}
3659,IssuesEvent,2015-10-29 16:04:49+00:00,38859116,pyhys/minimalmodbus,112723,photron,,,opened,close_port_after_each_call logic doesn't take exceptions into account,[],[],0,"The _communicate function assumes that the serial port is closed if close_port_after_each_call is set and tries to open it. But If it is already open the serial.open call will fail with an exception saying that it is already open.

This situation can be triggered if any unhandled exception occurs between the serial.open call and the serial.close call in the _communicate function. There are several places that can raise such exceptions:

* the serial.write call can fail with an SerialTimeoutException
* the local echo logic can raise an IOError
* I think in my case I also saw the serial.read call fail, even if the pySerial documentation doesn't say it could

Probably the easiest fix is to put all code in the _communicate function between the serial.open call and the serial.close call into a try/finally block and move the serial.close call itself in the finally part of it.",{},{}
