9299,IssuesEvent,2015-06-02 09:17:00+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,1698163,lnielsen,1157480,inveniosoftware,opened,docker: support for boot2docker,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_major', 'name': 'p_major', 'color': 'e11d21'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_bug', 'name': 't_bug', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],0,"In general the new docker+docker compose works very nicely. I've tested it on OS X with boot2docker and found some few issues.

**Problem 1** 
Boot2docker creates a minimal VirtualBox VM with docker installed on it and pipes all docker commands to that VM. 
Docker-compose bridges the containers ports to the localhost network interface on the docker host, which in case of boot2docker is localhost on the VM. This means that none of the ports are open to the VM host system (OS X in this case). 

The fix is quite easy as provided by @crepererum:

```
ports:
    - ""127.0.0.1:5000:5000""
```
->
```
ports:
    - ""5000:5000""
```

It makes sense when the docker host is also the developer machine that the docker containers ports are not opened to your entire LAN. So not sure what the best fix is here. Perhaps just add documentation for boot2docker or provide two different docker-compose files. 

**Problem 2**
Given that problem 1 is fixed, then there's still a problem that ``CFG_SITE_URL`` is set to ``http://localhost:5000`` in ``docker_boot.sh``. Perhaps the fix here is just to ingest ``CFG_SITE_URL`` 
via env variables similar to e.g. ``CFG_DATABASE_HOST``.",{},{}
9303,IssuesEvent,2015-09-04 11:56:00+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,119349,kaplun,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,RFC Invenio Matcher (legacy BibMatch),"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_BibMatch', 'name': 'c_BibMatch', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/RFC', 'name': 'RFC', 'color': '009800'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/s_INSPIRE', 'name': 's_INSPIRE', 'color': '207de5'}]",[],10,"BibMatch is a highly customizable Invenio legacy module that allows to check if a given record already exists in the system. This is of paramount importance in the context of a.g. a service such as INSPIRE where documents are aggregated from different sources and one desire to minimize the human effort in spotting record duplicates.

The implementation in Invenio legacy was mainly evolved as a set of calls to the native Invenio search engine, working around performance limitations, and completely bound to MARC.

If Invenio goes full steam for elasticsearch, bibmatch could in principle be simply reimplemented from scratch by having a thin layer that loads from a registry a set of queries expressed using elasticsearch dsl language: https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-dsl-py.

Elasticsearch natively support fuzzy searching, thus allowing to find most similar record.

Such module should at least offer a simple API that, given an incoming Invenio record, and a piece of configuration, should be able to answer with a weighted list of records in the system, *matching* the given record, i.e. answering the question whether there are records which are actually the same as the provided one (within the provided configuration).

Such configuration could vary a lot on a case by case, would depend on the particular instance of Invenio and on the particular document types. E.g. (article, preprint, proceeding, conference contribution, book, miscellaneous, note).

cc: @jalavik ",{},{}
