10801,IssuesEvent,2016-11-25 17:11:02+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,398875,neubig,2374376,clab,closed,L2 regularization might be buggy,"[{'id': 439661365, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/clab/dynet/labels/moderate%20bug', 'name': 'moderate bug', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}, {'id': 175078391, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/clab/dynet/labels/wontfix', 'name': 'wontfix', 'color': 'ffffff', 'default': True}]",[],4,"Hi, seeing that dynet uses global decay to implement sparse l2 regularizer. great work! But there seems still some problem.

To my understanding, the `L2WeightDecay` represents the `s_t` in the sparse sgd update methods:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/745499/20225536/c0e06e62-a7f8-11e6-9194-586400be2fd3.png)

If that is right, the `L2WeightDecay.update_weight_decay()` seems forget the `\gamma_t` in the above formula because the decay is only updated with `1-\lambda`. See https://github.com/clab/dynet/blob/master/dynet/weight-decay.h#L24-L29.

What's more, all the trainers in dynet (SimpleSGD, Adam, etc.) use the same decay method. But to my understanding, different optimization algorithms might have different decay factor. Taking adam for example:

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/745499/20226667/d01df908-a7fd-11e6-891b-a840da377398.png)

Please advise if I am wrong about the regularizer.
",{},{}
