11660,IssuesEvent,2018-01-20 10:41:34+00:00,70530854,awslabs/serverless-application-model,18738799,nmcbride1,3299148,awslabs,opened,Packaging CF template configuration files,[],[],0,"Hello,
In CodePipeline I have a Source stage (AWS CodeCommit), a Build stage (CodeBuild) and Deploy stage (CloudFormation create change set). I have a template.yaml, buildspec.yaml and template-config.json in the root of my repo. The template-config.json is a CloudFormation template configuration file that contains the values of the parameters I would like CF to use when generating the stack. Relevant snippets of these files are:

**template.yaml**
Parameters: 
  Env: 
    Type: String
    AllowedValues: 
      - dev
      - tst
      - prd
  UserEnv: 
    Type: String
Resources:
  myLambda:
    Type: 'AWS::Serverless::Function'
    Environment:
        Variables:
          USERENV:
            Ref: UserEnv
          ENV:
            Ref: Env

**buildspec.yaml**
build:
    commands:
      - aws cloudformation package --template template.yaml --s3-bucket <my artifact bucket> --output-template template-export.yaml

**template-config.json**
{
  ""Parameters"" : {
    ""Env"" : ""dev"",
    ""UserEnv"" : ""neil""
    }
}

The input artifact to the Build stage in my pipeline is ""MyApp"" (my repo). When the Build stage runs the CF package command will product an output like this:

[Container] 2018/01/20 09:20:21 Running command aws cloudformation package --template template.yaml --s3-bucket <my bucket> --output-template template-export.yaml

Uploading to 4f56d026bef150d783f33d96c010a546 
Successfully packaged artifacts and wrote output template to file template-export.yaml.
Execute the following command to deploy the packaged template
aws cloudformation deploy --template-file /codebuild/output/src911392013/src/template-export.yaml --stack-name <YOUR STACK NAME>

The output artifact ""MyAppBuild"" from the Build stage is used as the input artifact to the Deploy stage:

Template: MyAppBuild::template-export.yaml
Template configuration: MyAppBuild::template-config.json

The Deploy stage will then fail as the input artifact only contains the template-export.yaml file.

I'm unclear what I need to specify in template.yaml or buildspec.yaml to enable the Cloudformation template configuration file to be made available in the output artifact of the Build stage of the pipeline. 

Ultimately I'm trying to do what is described in the answer here, but making use of AWS SAM and the AWS CI tools rather than CLI commands:

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/41679588/how-to-handle-multiple-environments-in-codepipeline

Thank you.

",{},{}
11668,IssuesEvent,2018-06-27 21:18:06+00:00,70530854,awslabs/serverless-application-model,1882775,brettstack,3299148,awslabs,closed,Allow Inline Lambda Function Definitions,[],[],1,"It would be be great if we could define the code for Lambda functions inline. This functionality already exists for AWS::Lambda::Function resources and it is very convenient for things like Custom Resources that execute as part of the CloudFormation template or really simple Lambda@Edge functions.

Of course it would be understood if there needs to be a limit to the number of characters.

E.g. of current usage in a regular CloudFormation template

```
Resources:
  StaticSiteHelper: 
    Type: ""AWS::Lambda::Function""
    Description: ""Implements index.html support for directories &redirects to add a trailing slash""
    Properties: 
      Handler: ""index.handler""
      Role: !GetAtt LambdaRole.Arn
      Code:
        ZipFile: |
          exports.handler = (event, context, callback) => {
            const request = event.Records[0].cf.request;
            const matchArray = request.uri.match(/[^/]+$/);
              
            if (matchArray === null){
              request.uri = request.uri.replace(/\/$/, '\/index.html');        
              return callback(null, request);
            }	
            else if (matchArray[0].includes('.') === false){
              const response = {
                status: '302',
                headers: { location: [{ key: 'Location',value: request.uri + '/' }] }
              };
              return callback(null, response);
            }

            return callback(null, request);
          };
      Runtime: ""nodejs6.10""
      Timeout: ""30""
 ```",{},{}
