12910,IssuesEvent,2017-05-04 18:48:08+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Conda config file usage does not match documentation,"[{'id': 400449887, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source:ent', 'name': 'source:ent', 'color': '0e8a16', 'default': False}, {'id': 75418965, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/tag:documentation', 'name': 'tag:documentation', 'color': 'd4c5f9', 'default': False}]",[],2,"There are inconsistent behaviors in how the condarc file settings are applied.

FIRST issue:
Documentation [here](http://conda.pydata.org/docs/config.html#the-conda-configuration-file-condarc) says this:
""A .condarc file may also be located in the root environment, in which case it overrides any in the home directory.""

I found that not to be the case:
~/.condarc contents:

```
offline: True
channels:
  - intel
  - defaults
```

root condarc contents:
`offline: False`

conda info:

```
Current conda install:
               platform : linux-64
          conda version : 4.2.6
       conda is private : False
      conda-env version : 4.2.6
    conda-build version : 2.0.1
         python version : 3.5.2.final.0
       requests version : 2.9.1
       root environment : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3  (writable)
    default environment : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3
       envs directories : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/envs
          package cache : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/pkgs
           channel URLs : https://conda.anaconda.org/intel/linux-64/  (offline)
                          https://conda.anaconda.org/intel/noarch/  (offline)
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/free/linux-64/  (offline)
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/free/noarch/  (offline)
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/pro/linux-64/  (offline)
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/pro/noarch/  (offline)
            config file : /nfs/site/home/tmtomash/.condarc
           offline mode : True
```

As can be seen, the user-level condarc settings for ""offline"" and ""channels"" are both in effect, and the root environment condarc is being ignored.

SECOND issue:
Perhaps this is a feature, but it is unexpected. When specifying a configuration file by using the environment variable CONDARC, conda appears to merge the settings in the listed config file with those in the user's config file, rather than using only the contents of the specified file.

Config file at /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/envs/ipytest2/.condarc
`offline: False`

User config file is same as above.

```
Current conda install:
               platform : linux-64
          conda version : 4.2.6
       conda is private : False
      conda-env version : 4.2.6
    conda-build version : 2.0.1
         python version : 3.5.2.final.0
       requests version : 2.9.1
       root environment : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3  (writable)
    default environment : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3
       envs directories : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/envs
          package cache : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/pkgs
           channel URLs : https://conda.anaconda.org/intel/linux-64/
                          https://conda.anaconda.org/intel/noarch/
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/free/linux-64/
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/free/noarch/
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/pro/linux-64/
                          https://repo.continuum.io/pkgs/pro/noarch/
            config file : /localdisk/work/tmtomash/miniconda3/envs/ipytest2/.condarc
           offline mode : False
```

As you can see, the config file is listed as the file specified in CONDARC, and offline=False as that config file states, but the ""intel"" channel is still being pulled from the user configuration file.

Ultimately, I would like the ability to have environment-specific condarc files so that someone can create a single environment with the ""intel"" channel without that meaning ALL their environments now prefer intel packages. One potential implementation was to set CONDARC=<env_root>/.condarc, perhaps when ""activate""ing the environment. I'm not certain I can rely on any of the current config resolution mechanics, though.
",{},{}
12913,IssuesEvent,2017-03-09 19:18:08+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,Allow the forced installation of packages in environment with specification conflicts,"[{'id': 400449887, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/ent', 'name': 'ent', 'color': 'd93f0b', 'default': False}]",[],2,"Customers working with Conda environments can no longer use ""--force"" or ""--no-deps"" to create an environment with specification conflicts. This worked in Conda-3.x versions but no longer in Conda-4.x now that the solver considers the environment. Customers may need this in situations where they have vendor packages that are known to work with any version of a package but their specifications do not correctly state it(Vendor package is known to work with any version of Numpy above 1.6 but the vendor package specifies up to 1.8 while other packages need 1.9). Conda-4.x has caused breaking changes to enterprise customers although this was not necessarily what ""--force"" was meant for.

Is there a way to add a feature or functionality that will allow users to create an environment with conflicting specification if needed? This is seen as lost functionality in their use.

    conda install bokeh=0.9.2 numpy=1.8 --force

    conda install bokeh=0.9.2 numpy=1.8 --no-deps

",{},{}
