The ultimate failure there is that the test is hard-coded to look in a particular python version, which doesn't match the one that was installed for that subpackage.

### Steps to Reproduce
<!-- If the current behavior is a bug, please provide specific, minimal steps to independently reproduce.
     Include the exact conda commands that reproduce the issue and their output between the ticks below. -->
```
# start docker container - only python 2 shows this problem that I've seen
docker run -ti continuumio/miniconda bash
# install and remove conda-build (to install its deps)
conda install -y conda-build pytest pytest-cov git && conda remove -y conda-build
# clone conda-build
git clone https://github.com/conda/conda-build
# run test that reproduces the problem
py.test tests/test_subpackages.py::test_toplevel_entry_points_do_not_apply_to_subpackages
```

Note that these tests pass if you put a breakpoint in https://github.com/conda/conda-build/blob/master/conda_build/build.py#L1290, just before the environment creation happens.  These tests also pass on python 3 with conda 4.4, or with conda 4.3.33 on python 2.7.  Since it is a race condition, it's hard to say whether it actually isn't a problem there, or if we just get ""lucky"" with python 2.7 on conda 4.4.


## Expected Behavior
<!-- What do you think should happen? -->

All builds within a given matrix should be consistent, as they are all being fed the same dependency constraints.

