13023,IssuesEvent,2016-01-15 18:03:00+00:00,15889498,DiffSK/configobj,2079881,Teslafly,6395454,DiffSK,opened,Multiline lists leave much to be desired ,[],[],0,"Currently in configobj, multiline lists are implemented like so

```
[default]

list = '''
    item1,
    item2, #indented for clarity
    item3,
    etc,
'''
```

If items in the list are indented, when parsed the whitespace is also included, along with single line comments:

```
>>> from configobj import ConfigObj as cfobj
>>> example = cfobj('example.conf')
>>> print(dict(example))
{'default': {'list': '\n    item1,\n    item2, #indented for clarity\n    item3,\n    etc,\n'}}
>>> list = example['default']['list'].splitlines()
>>> list
['', '    item1,', '    item2, #indented for clarity', '    item3,', '    etc,']
>>> list = [x.strip() for x in list if x]
>>> list
['item1,', 'item2, #indented for clarity', 'item3,', 'etc,']
```
As you can see, there is a large amount of additional work needed to parse this list into a usable state. not to mention that single line comments don't work and commas aren't parsed correctly.

Contrast this with how configparser implements lists.

```
[default]

list:
    item1
    item2 #comments don't work
    item3
    etc
'''
```
and the code:
```
>>> import configparser
>>> example = configparser.SafeConfigParser()
>>> example.read('example2.conf')
['example2.conf']
>>> print(example['default']['list'])

item1
item2 #indented for clarity
item3
etc
>>> list = example['default']['list'].splitlines()
>>> print(list)
['', 'item1', 'item2 #indented for clarity', 'item3', 'etc']
>>> list = [x for x in stuff if x]
>>> print(list)
['item1', 'item2 #indented for clarity', 'item3', 'etc']
```

configparser also doesn't like comments in this case, but it still requires less work with less chance for error to parse it. This is beacuse it removes the beforehand whitespace and doesn't need a blockquote to define the value. merging the advantages of onfigobj and configparser, I propose the following behavior.

```
[default]

list:
    item1,
    item2, #indented for clarity
    item3,
    etc,
```

```
>>> from configobj import ConfigObj as cfobj
>>> example = cfobj('example.conf')
>>> print(dict(example))
{'default': {'list': ['item1', 'item2', 'item3',  'etc']}}
>>> list = example['default']['list']
>>> list
['item1', 'item2', 'item3',  'etc']
```

This preserves the congigobj list syntax, while allowing multiline expanded lists.
it does this by using the ':' to expect an indented list, removes the indent, and initially splits the list by newlines. Then it removes comments after the ',' seperator to allow for per-line comments. (before and it may be part of the data) 

What do you think about this behavior? Does it remain consistent with the configobj objectives?

This is probably an enhancement.
",{},{}
