13775,IssuesEvent,2017-04-25 22:25:06+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,476301,JamiesHQ,7388996,jupyter,closed,"ENH: Implement an enhancement badge/tag (nb functionality, Spark, real-time collaboration, dashboards, and more etc...)",[],[],5,"I believe this might be beginning to be addressed and here are my thoughts. As Github does not currently have this much-needed feature fully implemented(AFAIK), I think that having some mechanism for feature requests, ideas, suggestions, and enhancements would be very useful. Just going through my own repo, it seems that I've given some input on notebook functionality https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/issues/261 and  https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/8223 , PySpark integration https://github.com/jupyter/docker-demo-images/issues/41, real time collaboration https://github.com/jupyter/tmpnb/issues/139 , dashboards and more as have many other users/contributors. Features/ideas need to be easily locatable. It would be very useful to have a place or mechanism for discussion on Github of important and pending features and enhancements. 

It could be something as simple as active use of an enhancement tag/badge as I've seen in other scientific Python repos like Pandas(green color) or something like a repo for ideas where discussion would be in the comments. The subject header could include “ENH”. Also, there needs to be some delineation between major ideas(a few groupings-- see PR header) and enhancement/implementation fixes(possibly many). So, maybe two different tags for this. Or something more formalized from other discussions... Thoughts?
",{},{}
13782,IssuesEvent,2016-04-27 10:58:53+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,1012368,tudorprodan,7388996,jupyter,opened,The logging module in the notebook no longer seems to work properly,[],[],0,"When running the example from the python logging documentation page in a jupyter notebook, the messages go to the notebook console as opposed to the notebook's webpage output via the capture mechanism. Just create an empty notebook, run the example below, you'll see what I mean.

```python
import logging
logging.basicConfig(format='%(levelname)s:%(message)s', level=logging.DEBUG)
logging.debug('This message should appear on the console')
logging.info('So should this')
logging.warning('And this, too')
```

The logging module by default creates a `StreamHandler` object which will `if not stream: stream = sys.stderr`. A lot of modules use the logging module as in the example.

The problem is that the notebook actually inits the logging module before the output capture mechanism is set, so the default created `StreamHandler` actually has a reference to the original `sys.stdout`, before the notebook replaces it with it's own `ipykernel.iostream.OutStream`.

Shouldn't the notebook reset the logging module?

I've been looking into this because after an upgrade I noticed missing output from some stuff I was running often.",{},{}
