14571,IssuesEvent,2015-07-13 22:00:24+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,122831,coolaj86,9289019,letsencrypt,opened,Needs root.pem output.,[],[],0,"There needs to be a file created that has only the Root CA in it - no intermediates or server cert so that it can be pointed to with `curl` and other tools that won't have been updated with the Root CA at launch time.

It's also both useful and conventional for various applications, debugging, etc.

```bash
# with curl
curl https://example.com --cacert=/etc/letsencrypt/live/example.com/root.pem

# with openssl
openssl s_client -showcerts -connect example.com:443 -servername example.com
```

It's important that it doesn't contain the intermediates so that we know the intermediates are being served properly by the webserver that we're testing and not included in the client's chain.",{},{}
14575,IssuesEvent,2015-12-21 20:53:28+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,135698,Ikke,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Client hangs on connection via ipv6,[],[],1,"When executing the client, it tries to connect to the API via IPv6, which hangs indefinitely. 

acme-v01.api.letsencrypt.org also has AAAA records, which causes the client to try to connect to the API via IPv6. But the server does not accept connections via IPv6.

I ran strace on the process, which confirms this: 

> connect(4, {sa_family=AF_INET6, sin6_port=htons(443), inet_pton(AF_INET6, ""2a02:26f0:7b:48f::3d5"", &sin6_addr), sin6_flowinfo=0, sin6_scope_id=0}

Right now, the client is unusable for me.
Is there any way to force it to use IPv4?",{},{}
