17107,IssuesEvent,2016-10-25 23:30:37+00:00,53549881,anymail/django-anymail,639984,medmunds,17517617,anymail,opened,Postmark: Reply-To must be moved out of email headers,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/anymail/django-anymail/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],0,"Postmark's API disallows Reply-To in the message headers; it's only permitted in Postmark's ReplyTo param.

```python
# This works:
EmailMessage(..., reply_to=['reply@example.com']).send()

# This doesn't:
EmailMessage(..., headers={'Reply-To': 'reply@example.com'}).send()
```

Using the headers was the only option before Django added the explicit `reply_to` param. There may be some old code out there still using the headers approach.

Anymail should relocate Reply-To from the generic headers, if needed.
",{},{}
17121,IssuesEvent,2017-04-16 10:35:20+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,71352,uentity,17565521,pybind,opened,Incorrect objects construction with multiple inheritance,[],[],0,"I've decided to open a new issue, following already closed #797, because I was able to narrow down the error case and I think it's related to multiple inheritance and/or incorrect usage of trampolines, which I cannot detect.

Here's modified test case from #797:
```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

namespace py = pybind11;
using namespace pybind11::literals;

// classes
class objbase : public std::enable_shared_from_this< objbase > {
	int prop_ = 42;
public:
	virtual std::string name() const {
		return ""objbase"";
	}

	int prop() const { return prop_; }
};

class iface {
public:
	int n = 42;
	virtual int f() const = 0;
};

class mytype : public iface, public objbase {
public:
	std::string name() const override {
		return ""mytype"";
	}
	int f() const override {
		return 42;
	}
};
using sp_my = std::shared_ptr<mytype>;
using sp_cmy = std::shared_ptr<const mytype>;

// trampoline
template<class T = objbase>
class py_objbase : public T {
public:
	using T::T;

	std::string name() const override {
		PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(std::string, T, name);
	}
};

class py_objbase_ : public py_objbase<> {
	double pyprop_ = 42.84;

public:
	using py_objbase<>::py_objbase;

	double pyprop() const { return pyprop_; }
};

class py_iface : public iface {
public:
	using iface::iface;

	int f() const override {
		PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(int, iface, f);
	}
};

// bind mytype
class py_mytype : public py_iface, public py_objbase<mytype> {
public:
	using py_objbase<mytype>::py_objbase;

	int f() const override {
		PYBIND11_OVERLOAD(int, mytype, f);
	}
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
	py::module m(""example"");

	// bind objbase
	py::class_<objbase, py_objbase_, std::shared_ptr<objbase>>(m, ""objbase"", py::multiple_inheritance())
		.def(py::init_alias<>())
		.def(""name"", &objbase::name)
		.def_property_readonly(""prop"", &objbase::prop)
		.def_property_readonly(""refs"", [](const objbase& src) { return src.shared_from_this().use_count() - 1; })
		.def_property_readonly(""pyprop"", [](const objbase& src) {
			return static_cast<const py_objbase_*>(&src)->pyprop();
		})
	;

	// iface
	py::class_<iface, py_iface, std::shared_ptr<iface>>(m, ""iface"", py::multiple_inheritance())
		.def(""f"", &iface::f)
	;

	// bind mytype
	py::class_<mytype, iface, objbase, py_mytype, sp_my>(m, ""mytype"", py::multiple_inheritance())
		.def(py::init<>())
		.def(""name"", &mytype::name)
		.def(""f"", &mytype::f)
		.def_property_readonly(""n"", [](mytype& src){ return src.n; })
	;

	return m.ptr();
}
```
The main difference from #797 is that `objbase` now has `py_objbase_` trampoline instead of `py_objbase<>`. And `py_objbase_`, in it's turn, contains specific variable `pyprop`.

Now, if `objbase` is constructed directly, everything is fine:
```Python
In [1]: import example as e

In [2]: a = e.objbase()

In [3]: a.pyprop
Out[3]: 42.84
```
But `mytype` is constructed incorrectly:
```Python
In [1]: import example as e

In [2]: a = e.mytype()

In [3]: a.pyprop
Out[3]: 4.65557599738463e-310
```
More that that, in this concrete example if I change `mytype`'s constructor from `.def(py::init<>())` to `.def(py::init_alias<>())`, then Python crashes with segfault on `a = e.mytype()` line.

As you can see, I've added `multiple_inheritance()` tag to all exported types, but it makes no difference at all, because it makes sense only for `mytype` which already has multiple bases specified as `class_` template arguments.

Testes on clang 3.9.1, Python 2.7.13.",{},{}
17125,IssuesEvent,2017-09-21 17:18:11+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,11966765,ianhbell,17565521,pybind,closed,PYBIND11_MODULE namespace clash,[],[],4,"In PYBIND11_MODULE, if the name is also a namespace, compilation fails.  FWIW this was not a problem with the old-school PYBIND11_PLUGIN

E.g.:
```
#include <ChebMix/ChebMix.h>// (defining the ChebMix namespace)
...
PYBIND11_MODULE(ChebMix, m) {
    m.doc() = ""ChebMix module"";
    init_ChebTools(m);
    init_ChebMix(m);
}
```
yields
```
D:\Code\ChebMix\src\pybind11_wrapper.cpp(156): error C2882: 'ChebMix': illegal use of namespace identifier in expression
```

Is there a solution or workaround?",{},{}
17141,IssuesEvent,2018-03-10 04:09:43+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1322974,anntzer,17565521,pybind,opened,Replace sscanf by sscanf_s on Windows?,[],[],0,"## Issue description

PYBIND11_PLUGIN currently uses sscanf to parse the output of Py_GetVersion().  On MSVC, the use of sscanf triggers a warning:
> warning C4996: 'sscanf': This function or variable may be unsafe. Consider using sscanf_s instead. To disable deprecation, use _CRT_SECURE_NO_WARNINGS. See online help for details.

Obviously 1) the warning is spurious (the literal format used is totally safe) and 2) the programmer could, indeed, set _CRT_SECURE_NO_WARNINGS; but still, perhaps pybind11 could just use sscanf_s there?

## Reproducible example code

N/A",{},{}
