17629,IssuesEvent,2018-07-11 18:51:45+00:00,1732211,FactoryBoy/factory_boy,1190172,emanuil-tolev,20368050,FactoryBoy,opened,Different results when running unit tests using Faker one by one and all together,[],[],0,"When I run tests on their own, the data differs than when running the entire test module. Introducing an inability to run tests on their own seems unwise. What am I missing about using this library in tests?

```python
from faker import Faker
from unittest import TestCase

fake = Faker()
fake.seed(1)


class FakerTestCase(TestCase):
    def test_01(self):
        n = fake.name()
        assert n == 'Ryan Gallagher', n
        # when running this test on its own, it passes
        # when running the entire file, it also passes since it's the first one to be executed

    def test_02(self):
        n = fake.name()
        assert n == 'Ryan Gallagher', n
        # when running this test on its own, it passes
        # when running the entire suite, it fails. n is always ""Jon Cole""

    def test_03(self):
        n = fake.name()
        assert n == 'Ryan Gallagher', n
        # when running this test on its own, it passes
        # when running the entire suite, it fails. n is always ""Rachel Davis""
```

The test runner is nosetests. As you can see, nothing fancy is going on, like test execution in random order (which is a good idea to ensure tests are actually isolated from each other like, you know, ""units"").",{},{}
17639,IssuesEvent,2017-02-08 15:14:26+00:00,37137879,QCoDeS/Qcodes,2694199,giulioungaretti,20478252,QCoDeS,reopened,aborting a measurement,"[{'id': 222346531, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/QCoDeS/Qcodes/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': True}, {'id': 319815019, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/QCoDeS/Qcodes/labels/long-term', 'name': 'long-term', 'color': '207de5', 'default': False}, {'id': 414286649, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/QCoDeS/Qcodes/labels/mulitprocessing', 'name': 'mulitprocessing', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}]",[],6,"Currently it is hard to abort a running measurement. Pressing CTRL-C can leave the system (in particular the instruments) in an unusable state. The FAQ (https://github.com/QCoDeS/Qcodes/blob/master/docs/user/faq.rst) only mentiones ipython notebook. The original description (https://github.com/QCoDeS/Qcodes/pull/86/files) is only valid for a background measument, which is disabled by default.

PR #463 creates an abort measurement hook that can be used for proper abortion of a measurement.

@giulioungaretti @jenshnielsen @WilliamHPNielsen 



",{},{}
17682,IssuesEvent,2018-05-27 00:13:28+00:00,102973646,fastai/fastai,6740947,ashtonsix,20547620,fastai,opened,.half throws error during training when using batchnorm,[],[],0,"I've spent hours stuck on this!

![error: ""expected HalfTensor, recieved FloatTensor""](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6740947/40580534-0d6e9886-6138-11e8-9830-fb6ea2e66d78.png)

Inside FP16 I tried replacing:

```
self.module = batchnorm_to_fp32(module.half())
```

with

```
self.module = module.half()
```

& it worked, why isn't this the default?",{},{}
