18023,IssuesEvent,2017-12-26 10:43:55+00:00,80707765,SectorLabs/django-postgres-extra,450916,trifle,22373078,SectorLabs,opened,Return multiple rows after bulk_upsert?,[],[],0,"Hi,

(I've read the contributing guidelines and am sketching this out here to potentially work towards a pull request. A 24h reply definitely isn't necessary!)

I would like to do a bulk_upsert and use the returned IDs since it presumably saves a roundtrip.
From my admittedly naïve understanding, this should be possible.

Recapping my reading of the code:
`PostgresQuerySet` has a `bulk_upsert()` method that sets the `on_conflict` parameters.
Then, `bulk_insert` gets the insert compiler and executes it via `compiler.execute_sql(return_id=True)`, which is implemented in the compiler here: https://github.com/SectorLabs/django-postgres-extra/blob/c620fcd8903faeda61bee2a599ed18531f9fbdad/psqlextra/compiler.py#L45

The crucial part is:

```
        with self.connection.cursor() as cursor:
            rows = []
            for sql, params in self.as_sql(return_id):
                cursor.execute(sql, params)
                rows.append(cursor.fetchone())
```

Now, this *does* return for a bulk_insert. But it only includes one value since `cursor.fetchone()` yields one of the potentially many.

For example, using bulk_upsert code from the documentation yields the following query:

`[('INSERT INTO ""pg_mymodel"" (""myfield"") VALUES (%s), (%s) ON CONFLICT (""myfield"") DO UPDATE SET ""myfield"" = EXCLUDED.""myfield"" RETURNING *',
  ('beer', 'wine'))]`

This is a list of one query, which returns two IDs (""RETURNING *"" gets overrides by `_rewrite_ins
` later on, but that's irrelevant). From this query, cursor.fetchone() places one item in rows, which is then returned.

It should be possible to use `cursor.fetchall()` in case of an upsert (maybe always?), and extend rows instead. That should yield all affected rows.

I'm definitely no database / Django expert, so I'd be happy about any input and/or criticism here!
",{},{}
18040,IssuesEvent,2017-07-10 20:45:41+00:00,94917848,jupyterlab/jupyterlab-git,27600,ellisonbg,22800682,jupyterlab,opened,Create TS class with API to REST service,[],[],0,"There should be a standalone TypeScript class with methods for each git command/action. Each of those methods should take simple types, make the HTTP request and return a promise to the result. The API probably won't look very different from this:

https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/extensions/git/src/git.ts

But it will instead make HTTP requests to the server which has the python class with all of the logic.",{},{}
18041,IssuesEvent,2017-07-18 06:02:01+00:00,94917848,jupyterlab/jupyterlab-git,11495372,zzhangjii,22800682,jupyterlab,closed,Create specification for REST API,"[{'id': 644091014, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-git/labels/frontend', 'name': 'frontend', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}, {'id': 644091058, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jupyterlab/jupyterlab-git/labels/server', 'name': 'server', 'color': '0052cc', 'default': False}]",[],1,"Let's create a markdown document that follows the format of the Github API () to document the following aspects of the REST API:

1. URLS
2. HTTP verbs (`GET`, `POST`, etc)
3. Request JSON
4. Reply JSON
5. How errors are handled (HTTP error codes, error JSON)

I would create this in a new `specification` directory or something like that.

Some initial ideas we talked about:

URL:

`GET /git/status`

Request:

```json
{""repo"": ""/absolute/path/to/root/of/repo""}
```

Reply:

```json
{
    ""repo"": ""/absolute/path/to/root/of/repo"",
     ""files"": [
        {""x"": """", ""y"": """", ""to"": """", ""from"": """"}
    ]
}
```

Let's assume that all parsing will be on the server side.
",{},{}
