18555,IssuesEvent,2018-07-05 22:15:19+00:00,20664755,pymoca/pymoca,26876632,jackvreeken,33698687,pymoca,closed,Exponentially slow flattening with extends,"[{'id': 105737021, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMDU3MzcwMjE=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pymoca/pymoca/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],0,"Flattening ""Test"" in the model below will run out of time/memory due to exponentially growing deepcopying it seems.

```Modelica
model A
  Real x;
end A;

model B
  A y;
end B;

model Test
  model C
    extends B;
  end C;
  C c_1;
  C c_2;
  C c_3;
  C c_4;
  C c_5;
  C c_6;
  C c_7;
  C c_8;
  C c_9;
  C c_10;
  C c_11;
  C c_12;
  C c_13;
  C c_14;
  C c_15;
  C c_16;
  C c_17;
  C c_18;
  C c_19;
  C c_20;
  C c_21;
  C c_22;
  C c_23;
  C c_24;
  C c_25;
end Test;
```

Note that:
1.  Changing all instances of `C` to `B` will flatten very fast.
2. If `B` does not instantiate `A`, but instead only contains a statement `Real x;`, flattening is also really fast.
3. Moving the definition of `C` outside of `Test`, also makes everything fast again.

Timing is easy by looking at the messages printed with the following code in `ast.Class.copy_including_children`:

```diff
     def copy_including_children(self):
+        import time
         _parent = self.parent
+        ref = str(self.full_reference())
         self.parent = None
+        start_ = time.time()
         new = copy.deepcopy(self)
+        print(""Deepcopy of {} took {:.2f} seconds"".format(ref, time.time() - start_))
         self.parent = _parent
         new.parent = _parent
         return new
```
",{},{}
18560,IssuesEvent,2017-12-11 15:44:54+00:00,113770247,domainaware/checkdmarc,44679,seanthegeek,34143835,domainaware,opened,Raise SPFRecordInvalid if DNS queries for mechnisims exceed 10,[],[],0,"https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7208#section-4.6.4

>   Some mechanisms and modifiers (collectively, ""terms"") cause DNS
>    queries at the time of evaluation, and some do not.  The following
>    terms cause DNS queries: the ""include"", ""a"", ""mx"", ""ptr"", and
>    ""exists"" mechanisms, and the ""redirect"" modifier.  SPF
>    implementations MUST limit the total number of those terms to 10
>    during SPF evaluation, to avoid unreasonable load on the DNS.  If
>    this limit is exceeded, the implementation MUST return ""permerror"".
>    The other terms -- the ""all"", ""ip4"", and ""ip6"" mechanisms, and the
>    ""exp"" modifier -- do not cause DNS queries at the time of SPF
>    evaluation (the ""exp"" modifier only causes a lookup at a later time),
>    and their use is not subject to this limit.
> 
>    When evaluating the ""mx"" mechanism, the number of ""MX"" resource
>    records queried is included in the overall limit of 10 mechanisms/
>    modifiers that cause DNS lookups as described above.  In addition to
>    that limit, the evaluation of each ""MX"" record MUST NOT result in
>    querying more than 10 address records -- either ""A"" or ""AAAA""
>    resource records.  If this limit is exceeded, the ""mx"" mechanism MUST
>    produce a ""permerror"" result.",{},{}
