18640,IssuesEvent,2018-06-29 16:13:19+00:00,11309795,nmslib/nmslib,5798750,chapleau,37882366,nmslib,closed,query vector from hnsw index not found in top K ,[],[],6,"This is more a question than a bug report.

Building a rather large index with hnsw method, > 1M unit vectors (100d) with l2 space, M=40, efConstruction=1000, efSearch in 100-1000 range, default params otherwise (using v1.7.2)
For every vector in index, querying for top 1000 nearest neighbors. This works like a charm and the results are very accurate (and fast!) and because the vectors being queried are also used to create the index, the closest vector is always itself. However, there are very few cases ( < 100 ) where this isn't the case, i.e. the query vector is not in the top 1000 and the results are more or less relevant. 

My question would be, is this simply a consequence of the approximate nature of the method ? Something that has to do with how the heuristics work when building the index and all ?

Thanks in advance ! ",{},{}
18661,IssuesEvent,2018-07-12 06:31:31+00:00,3845895,fastavro/fastavro,13413617,lsyarn,40203918,fastavro,opened,load_shcema error when Parent.avsc has multiple  Child type,[],[],0,"`test_reading_after_writing_with_load_schema` work fine when `Parent.avsc` has only on Child Type field(Defined by `Child.asvc`).But when `Parent.avsc` has multiple  Child type, an exception will be raised:`TypeError: 'dict' object cannot be interpreted as an integer`。

Use schemas bellow can reappear this bug:
Parent.avsc
```
{
  ""type"":""record"",
  ""name"":""Parent"",
  ""fields"":[
    {
      ""name"": ""child"",
      ""type"": ""Child""
    },
    {
      ""name"": ""anotherChild"",
      ""type"": ""AnotherChild""
    }
  ]
}
```
Child.avsc
```
{
  ""type"":""record"",
  ""name"":""Child"",
  ""fields"":[]
}
```
AnotherChild.avsc
```
{
  ""type"":""record"",
  ""name"":""AnotherChild"",
  ""fields"":[]
}
```",{},{}
